{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569542"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22270"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22270"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.03,0.31,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111640"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15235"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93708"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111640"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine follow-up appointment. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and chronic kidney disease. Her regular medications include metformin, empagliflozin, perindopril, amlodipine, and atorvastatin. She works part-time as a librarian and lives with her husband.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 148/92 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 28 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 twelve months ago)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin:creatinine ratio (uACR): 28 mg/mmol (26 mg/mmol six months ago)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate reason for nephrologist referral in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Persistent uACR \u226530 mg/mmol","Resistant hypertension despite three antihypertensive medications","Potassium level \u003E5.0 mmol/L","eGFR \u003C30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2","Sustained decrease in eGFR of 15 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 within 12 months"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has chronic kidney disease (CKD) with multiple indications for nephrologist referral. While several factors warrant specialist input, the question asks for the most appropriate reason for referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EeGFR \u0026lt;30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate reason for nephrologist referral in this case. The patient\u0027s current eGFR is 28 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2, which corresponds to CKD stage 4. At this stage, patients require specialist nephrology input for comprehensive management, preparation for potential renal replacement therapy, and optimisation of CKD-related complications such as anaemia, mineral bone disease, and metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current \u003Cstrong\u003EuACR is 28 mg/mmol\u003C/strong\u003E, which is below the threshold of 30 mg/mmol that would indicate significant albuminuria requiring nephrologist referral. While any albuminuria in a patient with diabetes is concerning, this level does not meet the specific referral criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESustained decrease in eGFR of 15 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 within 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is also present in this patient (decline from 45 to 28 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 over 12 months). This represents a significant and concerning rate of kidney function decline that warrants nephrologist referral. However, the absolute eGFR value is a more immediate concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResistant hypertension despite three antihypertensive medications\u003C/strong\u003E is not demonstrated in this case. The patient is only on two antihypertensive medications (perindopril and amlodipine), and while her blood pressure is not optimally controlled, it does not meet the definition of resistant hypertension, which requires inadequate control despite three or more agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium level \u0026gt;5.0 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E (hyperkalaemia) is present but mild (5.2 mmol/L). While hyperkalaemia is a complication of advanced CKD that requires monitoring and management, it is not by itself a standard indication for nephrologist referral unless severe or refractory to treatment. The other factors present are more established indications for specialist referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn practice, this patient meets criteria for referral to nephrology for multiple reasons, including eGFR \u0026lt;30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2, significant eGFR decline over 12 months, and the presence of anaemia. The specialist would address comprehensive CKD management, including preparation for potential future renal replacement therapy, management of complications, and optimisation of blood pressure control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent nephrologist referral is indicated for rapidly declining eGFR (\u003E5 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 over 3 months) or signs of acute nephritis.","Nephrologist referral is recommended for patients with eGFR \u003C30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2, persistent uACR \u226530 mg/mmol, or sustained significant eGFR decline.","Resistant hypertension despite three or more antihypertensive medications is an indication for nephrologist referral in patients with chronic kidney disease."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from: https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93708"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22270"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93708"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T16:26:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T16:26:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15235"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111640"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"me